04262nam a22006615i 9780674059443DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20222011mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740594437 a10.4159/97806740594432doi  a(DE-B1597)583423  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aQM535b.L525 2011 7aSCI0360002bisacsh04a612/.912221 aLieberman, Daniel E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Evolution of the Human Head /cDaniel E. Lieberman. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource (768 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface: Heads Up -- t1 A Tinkered Ape? -- t2 The Skeletal Tissues of the Head -- t3 Setting the Stage: Embryonic Development of the Head -- t4 Modular Growth of the Fetal and Postnatal Head -- t5 Integration of the Head during Fetal and Postnatal Growth -- t6 The Brain and the Skull -- t7 You Are How You Eat: Chewing and the Head -- t8 Pharynx, Larynx, Tongue, and Lung -- t9 Holding Up and Moving the Head -- t10 Sense and Sensitivity: Vision, Hearing, Olfaction, and Taste -- t11 Early Hominin Heads -- t12 Ecce Early Homo -- t13 The Evolution of the Head in Homo sapiens -- t14 Final Thoughts and Speculations 14 Final Thoughts and Speculations -- tGlossary -- tReferences -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDan Lieberman has written an innovative, exhaustively researched and carefully argued book dealing with the evolution of the human head. In it he addresses three interrelated questions. First, why does the human head look the way it does? Second, why did these transformations occur? And third, how is something as complex and vital as the head so variable and evolvable? This book addresses these questions in three sections. The first set of chapters review how human and ape heads grow, both in terms of individual parts (organs and regions) and as an integrated whole. The second section reviews how the head performs its major functions: housing the brain, chewing, swallowing, breathing, vocalizing, thermoregulating, seeing, hearing, tasting, smelling, and balancing during locomotion. The final set of chapters review the fossil evidence for major transformations of the head during human evolution from the divergence of the human and ape lineages through the origins of Homo sapiens. These chapters use developmental and functional insights from the first two sections to speculate on the developmental and selective bases for these transformations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aHeadxEvolution. 0aHeadxGrowth. 0aHead-Evolution. 0aHead-Growth. 0aHuman evolution. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Human Anatomy & Physiology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z978311044221240uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674059443zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674059443423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674059443/original  a978-3-11-044221-2  HUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999c1893d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK